-- Access Modifiers
in java it is called encapsulation layers

1.private
2.protected
3.default
4.public

why is t used?
security and integrity?
It prevents "external" code from corrupting the internal state of your object

API stability: If you make everything public, developer never will use this code
because there are more chances that other developer will use this code or might be using it.
By making things private developer can change internal logic without breaking anyone else's code.

Cleanliness: It hides complexity. A user of your class only sees the
"buttons" and allowed to press.


-- Access modifiers strictly audited
-- private by default: Senior developer follows a rule: start with everything
private then only make it protected or public if needed if there is a specific, documented reason

public vs protected
public - can seen by everyone
protected  - can seen by everyone within package or different package
default - only seen within class and package
private - only seen by within class

